I think this needs to be Informational since no action is required.

A few things on the Message field -
- It should be something like:
  xyz.openbmc_project.Logging.Error.DeleteAll
  
- I think it would be good if this was still defined in an error yaml file, I think just doing it in yaml files in the yaml subdir of this repo is good enough since it isn't used by anyone else.

The phosphor-logging README has some info on the error files, or also look at the *.errors.yaml files out in phosphor-dbus-interfaces.

c
So this means you can only ever create one InfoLogsRotated?  What happens when it expires out?
Yes, it means that it created log when the logs were rotated first time. This log will eventually be rotated if the system keeps creating logs. Should we create another log if it is rotated?
Yes.  I'm not sure what the utility of it is otherwise.  You need to anticipate a machine staying up for years at a time.

We have devised an implementation wherein we initially create a rotated log during the first rotation. Subsequently, we ensure the preservation of this log from further rotations. By referring to this log, users can determine the starting point of the rotation. Do you have any thoughts or opinions on this particular implementation?
We update new patch for preserving "logRotated" log from being rotated.
Didn't the recursive call to createEntry already do that?
We don't need this line anymore with our new implementation.
Duplicate.
Done
"Real"?  @Matt, do you have a better name for this?
Maybe "ErrorLogsRotated" or just "LogsRotated"
Even "non-info" would seem to be fine to me.  But, they're all "real" no matter what the severity is.
Modified to nonInfo.
This isn't particularly useful of a "Tested" message.  What did you test and how?
Done

Doesn't this still mean we only get one rotated log?  How do we get a new one once the previous rotated log is itself purged out?

I'm still having a bit of a trouble understanding what the utility of this log is, especially if the machine has a very long uptime where we expect the logs to be rotated potentially many times.
We make the implementation preserving the log from being rotated. The explanation is on line 241 comment.
I'm confused by this code.  Where do these logs go if they're not pushed onto the list?
They will still be published on dbus. The list is utilize for tracking logs number by the size of list. Therefore, we can preserve the rotated log from being rotated.
This should probably be size_t?  Hopefully that is possible with the metadata parsing tools.
Done
If Matt is fine with this, we can merge it.  I'm not 100% satisfied but it probably isn't important.
(What I mean by this is that due to the implementation we only get the "rolled" messages once per BMC boot.  That doesn't seem very useful to me.)
This isn't a requirement from Meta?  Is it one built into IPMI and/or Redfish?
Looks good to me.

Hi Patrick,

The logs will keep rotating once the log numbers reach the maximum. The oldest log will be remove when there is new log created. Therefore, we decided to create the event log when first rotation occured for the record. It's hard to define when the second "rotated" log should be created.
I don't see this code as valuable in its current state then.  If we only ever get 1 rotation event, or we get 1 rotation event for each BMC reset, this isn't useful.
I think we could still go ahead with the log for event log cleared if desired.

Event when cleared seems useful
Event on every boot/restart once full seems a bit noisy
Event on on first fill (size-1=>size) might be useful?
Thanks. We leaved only log cleared for this patch. We will try to figure how to deal with the rotated event.
